g.text: You: Attempt to reconstruct what happened here.
You: Nothing more to see here. [Leave.]
Visual Calculus: The sign broke the vehicle's fall into the canal.
You: Look at the roof of the shack.
Visual Calculus: The black marks on the roof indicate that the vehicle *vaulted* from the crater to the roof of the shack.
Conceptualization: The SAMARAN BUTTER billboard still looks freshly painted, suggesting it took the plunge recently.
Visual Calculus: Judging by the size of the impact and the parallel lines of burnt rubber, the cause was probably a motor vehicle.
You: Look at the broken posts.
Visual Calculus: The vehicle soared through the air, hitting the billboard and upsetting the posts. Then it continued its flight, taking the billboard with it.
Perception (Sight): The crumpled SAMARAN BUTTER billboard still soaks in the canal, marked by tyre tracks.
Perception (Sight): A crumpled billboard reading "SAMARAN BUTTER" soaks in the canal. Two ugly lines mar the bright countenance of the blond boy depicted.
Kim Kitsuragi: The lieutenant looks on, waiting for you to wrap up your analysis.
Visual Calculus: It's about the right size, and the tyre marks look like they came from the skinny tyres frequently found on that motor carriage.
Visual Calculus: Still speeding, the vehicle made a loop and vanished into the fog along the coast.
Visual Calculus: Clearly. The motor carriage in question was a Coupris 40 -- mere minutes before it took a final voyage into the ocean.
Kim Kitsuragi: "Clearly, yes. Dwelling on it longer only makes it worse."

Encyclopedia: Goat milk butter. The Samaran terrain makes it easier to raise goats than cows, and the local goat farmers produce high-quality meat and dairy staples that add variety to other nations' diets.
Visual Calculus: There are two good candidates: the Coupris 40 and the Linnea G22.
Visual Calculus: Very sturdy but light motor carriage. More likely than most to survive that jump.
Encyclopedia: The Linnea G22 is not a particularly popular model due to its peculiar proportions, which the manufacturer's design team probably thought about for too long.
Visual Calculus: Side slip marks indicate that the vehicle was travelling up the crater at 35 km/h.
Visual Calculus: These match the tyre tracks you saw earlier -- *your* tyre tracks.
Visual Calculus: Just some tasteless advertising at the bottom of a canal. No use rubbernecking now.
Interfacing: The sign billboard has fallen on the water lock, keeping it open -- and thus out of order.
Perception (Sight): Whatever it is, the boy on the billboard seems very happy about it.
Visual Calculus: These look like the same tyre tracks I saw earlier -- in front of the Whirling-in-Rags.
Visual Calculus: The panel served as a take-off ramp.
Encyclopedia: The Coupris 40 is a very popular model with bank clerks, topping-pie delivery drivers, secondary school teachers, cops, strippers dressed as cops, undressed strippers...
You: Look at the opposite bank.
Visual Calculus: Now? You'd have to follow the tracks to be sure.
You: Look at the sloping metal roof panel.
You: What was the model of this phantom vehicle?
